Jameson Hannah is a junior outfielder for Dallas Baptist. He has plus speed and above average range in center field. Hannah has a tendency to get over his front foot when swinging, which robs him of some home run power. Despite this, he hits the ball hard. Hannah shows good pitch recognition at the plate and takes good at bats. His below average arm strength is his biggest weakness and hampers his ability in center. Hannah has a ceiling of an everyday centerfielder and could be an All-Star someday. He should be drafted in rounds 1-3.

It appears there is a book on Neustrom. He chased 2 sliders low and away. He also can get beat by + velo (94+). His swing is adjustable, but has lots of moving parts. Has often been bouncing balls into the ground. Can't seem to find the barrel lately. Lots of contact coming off the end of the bat. His swing has become more level as a result of him dropping his hands a bit in the load phase. It is more ideal for him to hit with a negative attack angle to take advantage of his + raw power.

Right now I'd give Neustrom a 5th or 6th round grade. Has solid tools across the board, but no carrying tool. Not sure the bat is there for RF, and some may not like him in RF due to a merely average arm. He's a future 4th OF with some upside.

Cropley had another big day. He hit a game winning HR (pull side) off a hung slider. Had 2 other hard hits to his pull side on fastballs. He also threw out a runner at second. Only mishap of the game was overthrowing the 2B on a steal attempt early in the game. Got him at a 1.94 pop time. He ran a 4.07 to first on Friday. RHH.

Cropley had shown an aggresive apporoach in the begining of the season, but has been much more patient in recent games. He showed some swing and miss on fastballs today which is somewhat concerning, but I've seen him hit greater velocity so often that it isn't a huge issue. Hit a massive home run to opposite field. The bat is legit.

Cropley was making very strong contact yet again today. He has very quick hands and gets inside balls and barrels them. Only one fell for Crop today, but it was still an impressive showing. He also gunned Kroon down at 2B on a laser throw. The arm is definitely above-average, 60 arm.

Cropley might be worth an underslot deal in the top 10 rounds. He posseses interesting tools for a catcher and has a track record of performance. He's an athletic player who can also play the OF. Biggest knock is that he hasn't called his own games.

University of South Florida_AT_University of Cincinnati_05/17/2018
COMMENTS: Villar isn't super tall, but does possess a thick lower half that should allow him to generate above average power in his swing. He looks a little stocky, and his weight seems like something that he will have to pay attention to for as long as he plays baseball. I'd put a Eugenio Suarez comp on his body/surface level profile, but Suarez started out as a skinnier/agile shortstop, so Villar has some work to do if he wants to remain on the left side of the infield. He won't blow you away with athleticism, twitchiness, or his arm, but I did see him show range to his glove side when he made a great diving stop to throw the runner out at first. I have him as a FV 45 at 3B, but I think that'll play just fine as long as he can keep himself from getting too heavy. At the plate, Villar stands closed off, with loose hands that rest near his back shoulder with a slight bat wiggle. A big leg kick initiates the loading of his hands, after which he explodes through the ball with solid upward plane to his swing. Standing closed off is a direct attempt to hunt for pitches middle/away, which he showed during his second at-bat when he roped a ball to RF. Standing closed off potentially leads Villar to be susceptible to heaters inside, but I think he has fast enough hands that he won't struggle catching up to those pitches to the point where it will hinder his ability to hit. He has some definite swing and miss issues, which I think is exasperated by his immature approach at the plate. He was a free swinger all day, and I think if he is more selective about which pitches he wants to drive, he can help to mitigate the swing and miss issues a little bit. I think Villar definitely gets drafted this year, probably in the 10-20 round range, and I will be interested to see how his tools play up in professional ball.

Gonzalez is a large framed infielder that has played multiple positions all over the diamond. His arm is his best tool and would profile at any spot. He showed good footwork and glovework in the field in my look. In his stance, he keeps his hands fairly quiet near his shoulder. Just before the pitch comes, he lifts his back leg, shifting his weight to the front, then uses a leg kick to shift his weight back. This double shifting of weight may cause timing issues, especially on offspeed pitches. He needs to improve his pitch recognition, as he swung over several breaking balls in my look. His large frame and good bat speed suggest he should have average power, but he will struggle to reach that level in games because of his swing and miss. His arm and defense give him a relatively high floor, but his ceiling is that of a low end regular. Without cutting down on the strikeouts, though, he will probably end up a defensive-minded utility infielder.

COMMENTS: Snyder is your prototypical power hitting first base prospect. He is built like Adam Dunn, and has massive forearms, but is much leaner than the former MLBer. There's really not much more room for growth for him, as he is a RS-Sr. and has maxed himself out at this point. He is more athletic than one might think for his size, but isn't great at first. He lacks the soft hands/reflexes necessary to field the ball consistently/scoop bad throws, and his arm is average at best. Watching him run down the first base line is like watching a car drive with square wheels, and I don't anticipate any gains in the speed department. At the plate, he has below average bat speed and bit of a lengthier swing. He has a wide open stance, and has quiet hands that he holds high by his back shoulder. The ball doesn't jump off his bat in the way that you would like to see, but the power is legit, and you can tell if he gets a hold of a ball it's going to go far. He has 19K's/19BB's on the season, and all of that contact has led to a super impressive slash line of .350/.417/.689 with 14 HRs. Despite that, I really wasn't overly impressed with him as a player, and am not confident in his ability to succeed at the next level. He is old relative to his competiton, and I am not sure what type of pitching he sees in the Horizon League. Someone will draft him, and I think he deserves that shot. I just don't see a very high ceiling here.

Excellent hitter.

COMMENTS: Berryhill's defense will be his carrying tool. He works well behind the plate, and frames the ball well. He needs a little more work blocking, as he let a few balls get by in my look that he should have handled. His arm is above average as well. His swing works well to lift the ball and get the most out of his raw power. The worrisome aspect of his swing, though, is his trigger is dropping the bat behind his head before bringing it back up in order to swing, and all that motion may make it harder to catch up to higher velocities. The present defensive ability gives him a relatively high floor, but if he can simplify his swing, his ceiling could be as a defensive-minded backup.

COMMENTS: Burdick doesn't have great size, but does posess a sturdy frame that should allow him to endure the gruelling nature of a long baseball season. He wasn't overly fast, but I'd be interested to get a few more home to first times on him to validate the below average times I clocked him at during the game. In the outfield, he looks perfectly capable of getting to all the balls he needs to, and flashed a borderline 60 arm from RF during in-and-outs. At the plate, Burdick stands with a wide open stance, with his hands up by his back shoulder. He has a slight bat wiggle that speeds up the closer the pitcher is to throwing the ball, and he initiates his swing with a smooth/rhythmic leg kick. He swings hard, and has natural loft and quick hands. I think at his peak, he will be able to hit for above average power, and his fast bat should allow him to handle more advanced pitching. He's not a five tool guy, or even someone to be overly excited about, but his actions at the plate paired with his strong arm/competency in the field should make him a draftable player down the road.

COMMENTS: Conley has a mature body for his age, with a thick lower half and solid upper body. He looks agile enough to stick at short, and showed good footwork and quick hands. He has an above average arm, and gets some impressive zip on the ball. For the most part, he didn’t get stagnant with his feet on his throws, although he did make a throw flat-footed in game and bounced the ball to first. He will have no problem finding a home at second if short doesn’t work out for him. He’s not exceptionally fast, although it is by no means a deficiency for him. He’s a switch hitter, and I got the chance to see both of his swings. Mechanically, they’re functionally the same. He has an open stance, and stands with his hands low, much like Francisco Lindor. He has a slight bat wiggle, and a short/compact swing that allows him to generate plus bat speed. I think his hands starting lower coupled with his fast bat will allow him to generate loft on his right handed swings, leading to a gap to gap profile. His swing isn’t built for power, and I doubt he ever runs into average power, although anything is possible if he makes the necessary adjustments. In the one at bat I saw him take from the left side, it looked like it was geared towards slapping the ball around the diamond, and not driving the ball. Throughout the game, Conley got a steady dose of breaking balls, which is to be expected by a high school pitcher with below average stuff. He did a good job of fighting off pitches, and showed a discerning eye at the plate. Overall, he looks like a player, and I think he showed enough for me to comfortably say he plays like a player too. Would want to see him again, though, since he had a relatively quiet game.

Dane Giesler is a first baseman who is in his redshirt-senior season at Indiana State. He bats left handed but throws right handed. Giesler shows average range at first base and is athletic for his position, which makes him more than the run of the mill first baseman. He has above average to plus raw power and above average contact and bat speed and solid plate discipline. Giesler has average speed and runs the bases well. There is not much more room for Giesler to grow, he is maxed out physically. Giesler has a wide stance and his stride while swinging makes it larger. Despite being a redshirt-senior, Giesler has produced enough to get a chance in pro ball, and he has the tools to make an impact. He should be drafted around the 20-30 round mark.

COMMENTS: OSU hit their BP rounds without any numbers visible on their warmups, which made it incredibly difficult to figure out who was who. I stumbled upon Dingler after watching his smooth righthanded stroke at the plate, and although he had a quiet game, I feel like he has the opportunity to be a big time player in the coming years. He's only a freshman, but posesses a tantilizing combination of height and a lean/athletic build. He has plenty of room to fill out, which when paired with his swing, leads me to believe he has above average raw power in the tank somewhere. He is listed as a catcher on their depth chart, but played CF during the game. He had a strong arm on his throws during in-and-outs, and showed enough for me to give him a 60. His footwork and reads looked fine during pregame, but he didn't have anything hit his way unfortunately. His home to first time left something to be desired in the speed department, but I'd venture a guess that he's a tick faster than I clocked him at. I'm really interested to see how he looks behind the plate (or if he plays there anymore), but don't think he will have trouble playing a solid LF/RF and a fringy CF. At the plate, he stands with his legs shoulder width apart in a slightly open stance. His hands are aligned with his back shoulder, and he has a soft bat wiggle pre-pitch. He has great actions to his swing, specifically how he starts his lower half during his bat load, which contributes to his plus bat speed. His swing allows him to drive through his lower half, and he generates natural loft in his swing. Dingler is really smooth across the board, and although he still needs refining on his approach at the plate, I really like his potential to develop 5 average/slightly above average tools at his peak.

GAME: University of South Florida_AT_University of Cincinnati_05/17/2018
COMMENTS: Genord was another impressive USF Bull that I got to see this weekend. He's got a great frame with big forearms and a sturdy lower half, and should have no problem enduring the grueling nature of a long baseball season. He is listed as a catcher/infielder on their website, but I only got to see him play 1B this weekend. He looked perfectly fine out there, but didn't really have much hit his way throughout the game. I'd be interested to see him behind the dish, as his bat paired with solid catching defense could make him extremely valuable. I didn't get a home to first time on him, but he doesn't exude plus foot speed, so I'm comfortable giving him a below average grade in that department. At the plate, he stands open, with some of his weight on the ball of his front foot. He holds his hands close to his body, with a smooth bat wiggle and his elbow cocked. He has an abbreviated leg kick that starts his swing, which is extrememly compact and quick through the zone. I don't think he will struggle with plus velocity at higher levels because of how fast his swing is. His last AB, Genord hit a monster HR to left field, and showed off his bat speed/natural loft in his swing. One final thing of note is that he was the leader of team stretches pre-game, which is something I like to see from catchers, and shows that he is a leader/respected by his teammates. I liked Genord at the plate, but his future for me will be determined by how he looks behind the dish defensively.

Givin isn't going to blow you away in any one area, but his dirtbag/gamer mentality helps his average tools to play up when he is on the baseball diamond. He has good size and long legs, although his upper body is a little skinny. He ran an underwhelming home to first time, but looks slightly faster than what I clocked him at. I didn't see anything from him defensively, but he has a .994 fielding percentage on the season and has only made 1 error. This leads me to believe he is perfectly competent at short, although he doesn't appear to have that typical agile/twitchy atheticism that professional shortstops need. I would need to watch him again to make a determination on if he has the tools to stick at short longterm. At the plate, he stands in the box with a wide stance, with his back elbow up and his bat at a 45 degree angle by his back shoulder. As the pitch is about to be delivered, his bat wiggle becomes more pronounced, although not to the point where it is a detriment to his timing. Although it is of little consequence, I feel like it is necessary to add to the dirtbag label I've given him by mentioning that he doesn't use batting gloves when he hits. He is a "foot down" guy, and barely lifts his leg when initiating his swing. There isn't a lot of natural loft in his swing, so I don't project him to run into much power at his peak, although his compact swing/above average bat speed should help him spray balls gap to gap. Givin is having a great junior year, but probably won't be an impact guy in pro ball based on his lack of standout tools.

COMMENTS: I have already scouted Grammes as a pitcher, but decided after talking to a scout at Wright St. last weekend to take a look at Grammes as a hitter, too. He had a quiet game overall, but flashed some of the same tantilizing yet unpolished skillset he also possesses on the mound. He looked small on the bump, but while I was standing at field level his lanky frame actually makes him look bigger at the plate. He has a wide stance that spans the entire box, and pairs that with a rhythmic bat wiggle pre-pitch. He has more of a pronounced load with his hands that you might normally see, but his bat speed is plus, leading me to believe that he won't have issues catching up to upper level pitching. He has a compact stroke and swings hard-- showing a concerted effort to drive the ball. While he does have 8HRs on the year/generates some natural loft in is swing, I think he saps some of his raw power because of his "get the foot down" mentality; there's more in the tank if he wants to make that adjustment. He struggled with breaking ball recognition throughout the day, and swung over the top of some chase pitches. The fact that he swings as hard as he does in the box, coupled with some inconsistency against breaking balls, translates to some inherent swing and miss. I think because of his quick hands he will make plenty of contact down the road, and the raw power is an added bonus. Defensively, I didn't see any balls hit to him during the game, but from what I've gathered, he's not great in the field. Not that fielding percentage is everything, but he's sitting at .897% with 9 errors on the year playing mostly at 2B. He isn't especially smooth and doesn't appear to have the quick reflexes and soft hands to play up the middle. He may fit in better at 3B based on the potential in his bat and his plus plus arm. As a draft eligible sophomore, teams will have to decide where Grammes profiles best (although there have been precedents set recently with two-way players), and if he is ready to make the next step to pro ball. Personally, if Grammes is available anywhere from round 10 on, I might draft him based on his physical tools, and figure out the rest after.

GAME: St. Clair County Community College_AT_Southeast Community College

COMMENTS: Hanford is a thick/musclular looking third basemen, who didn't really show me anything to defend his case that he could stick at third longterm. He looked perfectly capable of making the routine plays, but didn't have any chances that forced him to come in on a ball and make an athletic play on the run. Based on his body type/his apparent lack of quickness, I think he is probably a first basemen longterm. At the plate, he stands in an extreme crouch, with his hands held by his back shoulder and a loud barrel wiggle. A leg kick initiates his swing, and he is able to generate average bat speed when he attacks the ball. He ripped a line drive up the middle, and showed the ability to hunt fastballs and drive them. I think at his peak he will run into average power based on his strength/effective use of his lower half. Much like Reeser, though, I don't think he is a legitimate MLB prospect, as he doesn't have one tool that stands out. One name to watch on St. Louis is Alex King, who is a senior shortstop. He is athletic/quick for his size, and made several really nice plays at short that made me think he might be able to stick there. He also crushed a no doubter homerun, and generates plus bat speed on his compact swing. He has 7 HRs on the year, and is starting to get really hot at the plate. He is an intriguing prospect to keep an eye on.

COMMENTS: Harry III has a lot of positive qualities, including his abilities with regards to baserunning, fielding, and instincts. However, his bat is what will keep him from shining in the future. His bat is incredibly lackluster. His timing is way off and he needs to learn to stay back on the ball, especially when facing faster pitching. He struggles facing breaking balls which leads me to believe that he will struggle when facing even more powerful breaking pitches. He needs to be more patient at the plate if he wants to improve his hitting abilities and remain as a leadoff hitter. His best asset is his speed. He is bound to be able to use this speed to his advantage both defensively and on the basepaths. He is a very smart player and should be able to use this to his advantage for both baserunning and defense. At this stage, I can't envision Harry achieving any more success than that of a pinch runner in the minor leagues. Don't be fooled by the skewed numbers.

He has a slightly open stance, keeps his hand high with a lot of bat movement, and a long leg kick when swinging. Kelly has above average raw power with average contact tool and fringy pitch recognition. Kelly’s best tool is his blocking and receives. Despite being tall, Kelly gets low in his stance, and receives the pitch well and blocks everything in the dirt. Kelly has below average arm strength, but flashes average. Since Kelly is athletic, he could transition to first if his arm strength does not improve. Kelly’s ceiling is a backup catcher, and most likely an organizational catcher.

GAME: The Ohio State University_AT_University of Cincinnati_05/15/2018
COMMENTS: McGowan has been the best hitter on a much improved OSU squad this season, but I didn't come away extremely impressed with his overall skillset. McGowan has a mature/stocky frame and less than ideal height to pair with it. He looks strong in his legs/forearms, but also could stand to lean out a little-- which would help his movement patterns on both defense and offense to be less stiff. He DHed for me, but he is listed as a utility guy on their website. He took in-and-outs at 3B, where he showed average hands and an arm that was just good enough to grade at a 50. He looked clunky when he had to charge and throw on the run, and I'm skeptical if he could play the position at a higher level given his body type. As one can imagine, he's not very fast, which presents problems when you start to think of other possible spots on defense for him. His hands/reflexes might not be twitchy enough to play a good 2B, and he's shorter than what you'd like your 1B to be. I think he probably settles in at either 2B or LF (and may see time at 3B sparingly), but never plays average defense. At the plate, he has a wide stance and stands slightly open. His hands are held stiff by his back shoulder with his elbow cocked. During his swing, his back elbow raises even more dramatically, and his bat head slightly wraps around his head. I think this wrap helps him to generate upward plane on his swing, but also slows his hands down during his swing. A slight leg kick helps his hips drive through the ball, although I still don't love his actions at the plate. He does appear to have an advanced feel of the strike zone, and took controlled hacks at pitches he thought he could drive (mostly fastballs), which helps his hit tool play up for me. I put a 55FV on his hit tool, but that is pretty generous, and if there was ever a tweener between a 50-55, McGowan would be it. He is a positionless bat first guy with holes in his swing and a bad body, which isn't super intriguing to MLB teams. That's not to say he doesn't have a few decent tools, or that he couldn't drastically alter his body through work in the weightroom/proper nutrition. I just am not super excited by his overall makeup.

GAME: Brookline High School_AT_Newton North High School_04/23/2018
East High School_AT_Judge Memorial Catholic High School

COMMENTS: For the most part, my impression of McVey was the same this time around as it was the last time. He's really struggled at the plate this year, and looked out of sync for me today. He's servicable at third/can make all of the routine plays, but I think his bat/skillset would fit better at second (or even in LF). He's faster than his home to first time showed, considering the fact that he slowed down when he got close to the bag. He doesn't have great size, and is a "dirtbag" type of player. He has an open stance at the plate, with his feet spread a little wider than shoulder width apart. He holds his hands high with a small bat wiggle, and an aggresive leg kick initiates his swing. The leg kick allows him to generate above average bat speed, and make the most out of his thinner frame. He has good plane in his swing that will help him extra base hits. I still like his longterm ability to hit despite the struggles this year, but don't think he will run into much power ever.

GAME: University of Nebraska at Kearney_AT_University of Colorado, Colorado Springs

COMMENTS: Meehan is very small, and has a slight frame with skinny arms and legs. I don't see much more opportunity for him to mature physcially/add muscle, which isn't ideal. I didn't get much of a chance to see him challenged defensively in the field, but he looked perfectly capable of playing an average 2B, where his solid yet unspecatular arm will play fine. He shifted over to shortstop in the middle of the game, but that is merely semantics; he is not a shortstop. His home to first time was slow, but that is because he stopped running as he neared the bag. He is a twitchy/quick player who has above average speed, which will help make up for his underwhelming frame. At the plate, he has a loud bat wiggle pre-pitch, and bounces his front foot up and down simultaneously. He has a quick bat/swings hard, and generates good upward plane on his swing that will help him hit gap to gap. He has 6 homeruns this year, but I am skeptical he ever develops 50 power. He was out of sync at the plate all day, reaching for almost everything and only squaring up one ball. While it may not be the best comparison, his quirky nature at the plate almost reminds me of Hunter Pence, albeit with much less bat control/feel to hit. It will be interesting to see how many home runs he ends up with this year. I like him as a player, but not sure if he has the necessary tools to make it.

Vanderbilt commit Nick Northcutt's name has been mentioned as a potential selection in the first 3-5 rounds of the MLB draft this June. While I didn't leave blown away, there are quite a few things to like about his game, mainly with his bat. Northcutt has a stumpy/mature frame, and really doesn't look like a prototypical athlete. He is about to turn 19, which makes him old relative to his competition, not to mention he legitimately looks like a college player out there. I wouldn't project much more with his body, although I do think his underwhelming speed might tick up once he develops some lean muscle. Defensively, he pairs below average twitchiness/athleticism with a plus arm, a combination that yields a 45 grade for his defense. He should be able to make most of the plays, but his lack of consistent soft hands and clunky movement at times will hinder him from ever becoming an average 3B. I really don't know where you play him, because he's probably too slow to play a corner outfield spot. Ideally, he sticks at 3B, where he increases his value defensively playing a tougher position than one like 1B. At the plate, Northcutt sets up with his feet wider than shoulder width, with his back leg angled inwards. He has a quiet bat pre-pitch, and his leg kick and hands work together in sync when he is gearing up to swing. His mechanics look a lot like Josh Donaldson's, and his swing generates similar upward plane. His fast hands were evident when he swung, despite the fact that he didn't truly square up any balls today. He used wood the entire game, and at one point he weakly hit a high fastball and drove it into deep center, showing off some of the raw pop he is known for. One thing that really stood out to me is how mature his approach at the plate is. He didn't take one bad swing the entire game, and showed an advanced feel of the strike zone/getting the barrell to the ball. This feel for hitting is what makes me confident that he will be able to swing it at the next level, even if he is somewhat of an enigma defensively.

Powell is only a junior, but as a recent UC commit, I figured I would take a look at him. I came away impressed at some of his overall tools, but he is still raw as a player. He has a slight frame and isn't super tall, but he is still young and will have time to grow/put on muscle as he matures. Defensively, he averaged a 2.03 pop time for me, but two outlier data points might have made the average a little higher than it truly was. He was borderline sub-2, with an above average arm that he was able to utilize to place throws perfectly in front of the bag. His arm action wasn't necessarily clean, but it gets the job done. He was 1/2 on the day with stolen base attempts. He has good hands, and shows the reflexes to snatch balls in an attempt to frame them. He doesn't "stick" his frames consistently, receives the ball too close to his body, and struggled at times to block balls. I would expect him to improve as he becomes more experienced, though, and think he will be an above average catcher down the road. I didn't get a home to first time on him, but his speed looked underwhelming. At the plate, stands with his feet shoulder width apart in an open stance. He keeps his hands close to his back shoulder, with a controlled bat wiggle pre-pitch. His slight leg kick initiates his swing, which is compact and stays through the zone well. He has quick hands, and gets the barrell to the ball well for a kid his age. He's got some loft to his swing, but simply isn't strong enough to drive it for game power at this point. I think at his peak, he will develop a borderline plus hit tool, and slightly below average power. I have seen three prep catchers this spring (including Tyler McDonough and Keegan Fish), and I think Powell is a nice mixture of both; not quite as projectable at C as Fish, and not quite as good of a hitter as McDonough.

Reeser is having a successful season in terms of statistics and is a good college player, but I don't see him as a potential MLB guy. He is a college first basemen who is small in size and has a stocky build. He is definitely not athletic enough to play anywhere else on the diamond, which doesn't bode well when you consider the rest of his skillset is unimpressive too. At the plate, he looks competent, and actually hit a ball pretty hard between short and third for a single. He stands with most of his weight already loaded onto his back leg, and has quiet pre-pitch mechanics that initiate his swing. He has average bat speed and a compact swing that has decent plane to it, and will probably run into some hits throughout a given season. Overall, though, he doesn't have any tools that stand out, and isn't a potential MLB prospect in my opinion.

COMMENTS: Smith has a thick frame and mature looking body, giving off the vibe that he is "country strong." He is a college first baseman, which isn't ideal, and given his frame/lack of quickness he probably can't play anywhere else on the diamond. At the plate, Smith hits from a slight crouch, with his hands held chest high. He flicks his barrell back and forth pre-pitch, and loads his hands using a lengthier semi-circular motion. It is not horrible, but I could see it hindering him against plus velocity if he isn't precise. He's got above average bat speed, and hits the ball hard when he makes contact with it. His first AB he mashed a homer 400+ feet dead center, and I feel comfortable projecting him for above average power in the future. Smith doesn't stand out, but he has a good bat and still has two more years of eligibility left. Unfortunately, being a college first basemen who has a fringy hit tool and some power won't make you a super desirable player in the June draft.

His swing path is excellent, he shifts his weight to his back leg well, he creates a rubberband effect with his hands, and he has great bat speed. He should continue improving his swing at the next levels of competition. The rest of his game is average right now, but should continue to improve with more practice and repetitions. He is solid defensively as a center fielder and runs the bases fairly well. My two biggest concerns are his lack of size and his lack of aggressiveness at the plate. He almost seems to lack a killer instinct, which may come back to haunt him against pitchers who will go right after him. Overall, however, Veal should prove himself to be a solid asset for any organization in the future.

COMMENTS: Medium frame with athletic projectable present build. Small leg lift and gets foot down early. Middle away approach flashes some strength. Wiemer has great size for his age, and will definitely fill out as he gets older. He's perfectly fine in LF, but won't blow you away with his defense or arm. He made a few bad reads today, was pulled in the 6th, and immediately went to the locker room. That leads me to think he might have been hurt/sick, which could have contributed to him not being super sharp at the plate or in the field. At the dish, Wiemer has loud mechanics. He stands upright, with his hands held by his shoulders. His leg kick and hands work in sync, with his hands dropping down/loading when he begins his leg kick. He uses his lower half well to drive through the ball, and generates plus bat speed/raw power. Normally I like quiet mechanics, but Wiemer makes the swing work for him. His pull heavy approach, as well as the numerous moving parts in his swing, might keep him from ever developing an average hit tool, but the power is definitely there. He is only a freshman, and will be someone to watch in the coming years. He's a little stiff in the field, and could make a move to first down the road, where his bat would play nicely.
